message.content:
A leopard is a large carnivorous feline found in sub-Saharan Africa and some parts of Asia.
Known for its spotted coat, a leopard's fur is typically a golden-yellow color with black spots and rosettes.
Leopards have a muscular, agile build and their sharp claws allow them to climb trees with ease.
Their distinctive facial features include round ears and strong jaws with prominent whisker pads.
Leopards are solitary hunters and feed on a variety of prey such as antelopes, deer and smaller mammals.
Their impressive night vision and stealthy approach make them successful hunters, capable of taking down prey larger than themselves.
Leopards can be found in a variety of habitats including forests, savannas and mountains, and can even adapt to living near human settlements.
